    <li class="publication  article">
  <cite><span class="title">
  <span>Ultrahigh-resolution imaging reveals formation of neuronal SNARE/Munc18 complexes in situ.</span>
  <i>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America</i>
</span>
<span class="authors">Pertsinidis, A., Mukherjee, K., Sharma, M., Pang, Z. P., Park, S. R., Zhang, Y., Brunger, A. T., Südhof, T. C., Chu, S.</span>

<span class="details">
   <span class="year">2013</span>; <span class="volume">110 (30)</span><span class="pages">: E2812-20</span>
</span></cite>
    <div class="detail">
      <h4>Abstract</h4>
  <p class="abstract">Membrane fusion is mediated by complexes formed by SNAP-receptor (SNARE) and Secretory 1 (Sec1)/mammalian uncoordinated-18 (Munc18)-like (SM) proteins, but it is unclear when and how these complexes assemble. Here we describe an improved two-color fluorescence nanoscopy technique that can achieve effective resolutions of up to 7.5-nm full width at half maximum (3.2-nm localization precision), limited only by stochastic photon emission from single molecules. We use this technique to dissect the spatial relationships between the neuronal SM protein Munc18-1 and SNARE proteins syntaxin-1 and SNAP-25 (25 kDa synaptosome-associated protein). Strikingly, we observed nanoscale clusters consisting of syntaxin-1 and SNAP-25 that contained associated Munc18-1. Rescue experiments with syntaxin-1 mutants revealed that Munc18-1 recruitment to the plasma membrane depends on the Munc18-1 binding to the N-terminal peptide of syntaxin-1. Our results suggest that in a primary neuron, SNARE/SM protein complexes containing syntaxin-1, SNAP-25, and Munc18-1 are preassembled in microdomains on the presynaptic plasma membrane. Our superresolution imaging method provides a framework for investigating interactions between the synaptic vesicle fusion machinery and other subcellular systems in situ.</p>
